<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many tons of asphalt do I need?", answer: "Multiply length by width by depth in feet, then multiply by the unit weight of hot-mix asphalt (about 145 pounds per cubic foot for dense-graded mixes) and divide by 2,000 to get US tons. For a 50x12 ft driveway at 3 inches thick, that is 150 cubic feet × 145 lb = 21,750 lb ≈ 10.9 US tons." },
  { question: "How thick should an asphalt driveway be?", answer: "Residential driveways are typically 2 to 3 inches of compacted asphalt over 4 to 8 inches of compacted aggregate base. Heavier vehicles and commercial traffic require 3 to 4 inches of asphalt. Parking lots for cars use 2 to 3 inches; truck traffic needs 4 inches or more with a stronger base." },
  { question: "How much does asphalt weigh per cubic yard?", answer: "Dense-graded hot-mix asphalt weighs about 145 lb/ft³, which is roughly 3,915 lb or 1.96 US tons per cubic yard. Metric: about 2,322 kg/m³. Open-graded mixes used for porous pavement are lighter at around 120 lb/ft³." },
  { question: "How big is a typical asphalt truckload?", answer: "Standard dump trucks haul about 20 US tons (18 metric tonnes) of hot-mix asphalt. Larger trucks and trailer combinations can carry 25 to 30 tons. Plan your pour so trucks arrive at the rate your crew can lay and compact the mix before it cools below ~275°F." },
  { question: "Can I use this calculator for cold patch or millings?", answer: "Yes, but adjust the density. Cold patch is about 140 lb/ft³, and compacted recycled asphalt pavement (RAP) millings run 120 to 140 lb/ft³. Enter the correct density for the most accurate tonnage estimate." }
]) %>

